up, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Montigny","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Henri, Jacques, Normand, Remi.","French: habitational name from (Le) Montigny, the name of several places in various parts of France (from a Gallo-Roman estate name, <i>Montiniacum</i>, formed either from a personal name or from a derivative of <i>mons</i> ‘mountain’ + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>). Compare   Demontigny  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Demontigny","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Aurele, Gilles, Jacques.","French: habitational name, with fused preposition <i>de</i> ‘from’, for someone from any of several places in various parts of France named Montigny (see   Montigny  )."]}]},{"name":"en","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 任, based on its Mandarin pronunciation, see   Ren   1.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 全, based on its pronunciation in Shanghai dialect, see   Quan   2.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 曾, see   Zeng  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ren","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Yong, Hong, Hui, Chuan, Gang, Guang, Jian, Liang, Lihua, Ning, Qing, Chang, Min, Shen, Yiming.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 任, a term for women's rank of peerage in ancient Chinese: (i) it is said that the surname can be traced back to one of the 25 sons of the legendary Huang Di, the ‘Yellow Emperor’ (<i>c.</i> 27th century  BC ). (ii) from Ren (任), the name of an ancient state (located in Renxian in Hebei province) granted to Yu Yang, said to be a son or grandson of the legendary Huang Di, the ‘Yellow Emperor’ (<i>c.</i> 27th century  BC ). His descendants adopted the name of the state as their surname. (iii) from Ren (任), the name of a state (located in Shandong province) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ).","English: variant of   Renn   2."]}]},{"name":"Eustache","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Eustace</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"III","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Japanese Yuko, Aiko, Hideaki, Hiroki, Hiroyuki, Isamu, Kaoru, Katsumi, Keiichiro, Kenji, Masako, Masayuki.","Japanese: variously written, sometimes with characters used phonetically; the most probable meanings are 仁井 ‘benevolent well’, 新居 ‘new residence’, or 新井 ‘new well’. It is not common in Japan."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Eustache III de Montigny en Ostrevent was born in 1205, in Montigny-en-Ostervent, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France, his father, Robert I de Montigny-en-Ostrevent, was 23 and his mother, Jehanne d'Amerval, was 17. He had at least 1 son with Madeleine de Trith. He died in 1267, at the age of 62."},"et":{"1205–1267":"1205–1267","1201–1268":"1201–1268","1229–1292":"1229–1292","1182–1249":"1182–1249","1188–1239":"1188–1239","1239":"1239","1205":"1205","1249":"1249","1268":"1268","1267":"1267","1201":"1201","1188":"1188","1182":"1182","1292":"1292","1229":"1229","Montigny-en-Ostrevent, Nord, Hauts-de-France, France":"Montigny-en-Ostrevent, Nord, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Montigny-en-Ostervent, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Montigny-en-Ostervent, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1205–1267":"1205–1267","1201–1268":"1201–1268","1229–1292":"1229–1292","1182–1249":"1182–1249","1188–1239":"1188–1239","1239":"1239","1205":"1205","1249":"1249","1268":"126